Churn Probability Prediction at Small Scale

Tony Yao-Jen Kuo

July 21, 2016

Summary

This document is the first draft of churn probability prediction collaborated by Customer Insight Team in Seoul and Data Science Team in Shanghai. According to our definition, we have 8.7 million of active customers at the beginning of February, 2016, and 2.6 million of them would churn within the next 4 months. Weve built 2 classification models using Decision Tree from rpart package and Random Forest from randomForest to predict the probability. Key takeaways are:

Decision Tree
Accuracy: 0.94
Precision: 0.89
Important predictors: DAYS_LAST_WEB_VISIT
DAYS_FIRST_PURCHASE
DAYS_LAST_PURCHASE
COUPANG_CASH_USAGE
Random Forest
Accuracy: 0.97
Precision: 0.97
Important predictors: DAYS_LAST_WEB_VISIT
DAYS_FIRST_PURCHASE
DAYS_LAST_PURCHASE
ACQUISITION_CHANNEL
ROCKET_CT
COUPANG_CASH_USAGE

Predictors

Weve collected a total of 56 predictors from different data sources(PDA and Hive) and the main categories are:

  • Purchase history by customer
  • Purchase history by customer and product categories
  • Engagement data by customer
  • Acquisition data by customer
  • Acquisition data by customer and product categories
  • Demographic data by customer
  • Customer service data by customer and contact types
  • Product review data by customer

Data at Small Scale

Weve extracted 105,000 observations with 80,000 active customers and 25,000 churned customers randomly. The relative proportion matches our total observations. After tons of manipulation, cleaning, and imputations, the data structure looks like:

We shuffled the data and separate them into train and test with a traditional 70/30 split. We will build our model based on train data and validate on test data. Let us take a glimpse of the dimensions of train and test, respectively:

## [1] 73500    57
## [1] 31500    57

First Model: Decision Tree

Before jumping into random forest, let us quickly fit a decision tree using rpart package first.

tree <- rpart(formula = CHURN_FLAG ~ ., data = train, method = "class")

And the confusion matrix is pretty nice:

Under default setting (complexity parameter sets at 0.01 and using GINI impurity to split data), the top predictors are:

  • DAYS_LAST_WEB_VISIT(Engagement)
  • DAYS_FIRST_PURCHASE(Acquisition)
  • DAYS_LAST_PURCHASE(Purchase history)
  • COUPANG_CASH_USAGE(Purchase history)

Second Model: Random Forest

Random Forest model in R does not allow NAs.

Our review data has a lot of(Approximately 95%) missing value that cannot be imputed. Since the rating of product review is at a scale of 1 to 5, if we impute NAs with 0s or median, which might distort the predictors. So before modeling random forest, we will just exclude the predicotrs:

  • MIN_RATING
  • MAX_RATING
  • AVG_RATING

And the same reason also applies to engagement data:

  • DAYS_LAST_ANDROID_VISIT
  • DAYS_LAST_IOS_VISIT

Random Forest model in R does not allow factors with more than 32 levels, either. So we will impute the predictor ACQUISITION_PUBLISHER:

## 
##                 App Push               Daily Mail                  Daum SA 
##                      678                     1209                      609 
##                Google SA    Mobileweb Full Banner Mobileweb Quarter Banner 
##                      115                      777                       59 
##                 Naver SA                  Organic         Other Publishers 
##                     3267                    55938                    10848
